My meme

Inspo_meme

The key components from the inspo meme changing the side three images by changing the website address and changing the right side white boxes on the side with words that is relatable to the right images ive applied similar layout accordingly with the frames, ive also applied a font and colour to the background and the text and added a font.

#Load Packages to run functions

library(magick)

#Labelling the images into object values 

Disappointed <- image_read("https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2020/05/20/05/43/offense-5194799_1280.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(750)

Meme_women <- image_read("https://static.wixstatic.com/media/f6bccd_27c5342e39874f3ba9727eb84ba91e3a~mv2.png/v1/fit/w_491%2Ch_326%2Cal_c%2Cq_80,enc_auto/file.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(750)

Lost_child <- image_read("https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2016/10/07/15/58/child-1721906_1280.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(750)

#Creating the right side text 

first_text <- image_blank(width = 500, 
                          height = 500, 
                          color = "#F8BBD0") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "When you can't figure out\n what is wrong with the code",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 40,
                 font = "Comic Sans",
                 gravity = "center")

second_text <- image_blank(width = 500, 
                         height = 500, 
                         color = "#CE93D8") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Social Media",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Comic Sans",
                 gravity = "center")

third_text <- image_blank(width = 500, 
                       height = 500, 
                       color = "#B39DDB") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Stats 220",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Comic Sans",
                 gravity = "center")

# Create each image to text pair and flatten the image sequence
pair1 <- image_append(c(Disappointed, first_text), stack = FALSE) %>%
  image_scale("500x500") %>%
  image_flatten()
pair2 <- image_append(c(Meme_women, second_text), stack = FALSE) %>%
  image_scale("500x500") %>%
  image_flatten()
pair3 <- image_append(c(Lost_child, third_text), stack = FALSE) %>%
  image_scale("500x500") %>%
  image_flatten()

# Stack the pairs vertically
combined_image <- image_append(c(pair1, pair2, pair3), stack = TRUE)

# Write the combined image to a file
image_write(combined_image, "confused_meme.png")
# creating a vector for the counts
counts <- 1 : 3 %>% as.character()
heart_image <- image_read("https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2016/02/10/21/57/heart-1192662_1280.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)

# creating each frame, where the text comes from the counts vector
frame1 <- heart_image %>%
  image_annotate(text = counts[3],color = "#F8BBD0", size = 100, gravity = "center") %>%
  image_scale(300) %>%
  image_extent("500x500")

frame2 <- heart_image %>%
  image_annotate(text = counts[2],color = "#CE93D8", size = 100, gravity = "center") %>%
  image_scale(400) %>%
  image_extent("500x500")

frame3 <- heart_image %>%
  image_annotate(text = counts[1],color = "#B39DDB", size = 100, gravity = "center") %>%
  image_scale(500) %>%
  image_extent("500x500")


# Create a list of frames for the animation
frames <- list(frame1, frame2, frame3, pair1, pair2, pair3)

# Add a transition effect between frames
frames <- lapply(frames, image_morph, frames = 0.5)

# Create the animation
animation <- image_animate(image_join(frames), fps = 0.5)

# Write the animation to a file
image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")

Creativity

For this project, Ive tried to add functions based from the foundation functions in the magick package, for example by following the script of the image_annotate function and making adjustments to the sizing that meant how too fill in the white regions with colours and added HTML colours also by the ability to rearrange the boxes based on the vertical and horizontal axis changes the meaning of the meme itself with the stack functions of being TRUE or FALSE. By adding new functions like image_flatten to merge the layers together into a single layer to make the meme on one sheet.

For the Github repository, Ive changed the the layout with three subheadings by utilizing the # functions and added links that incorporate the profile and professional profile

For the animation section Ive made adjustments with the images to animate and added more frames to flow with the context of the meme by changing the starting frames by pairing two separate sets in and merging them together.

Ive also added background design to the css and created font with colour and created a second heading with h2 elements
